THOUGHT
The user wants me to fix a crash in the LLVM `loop-unroll` pass.
The crash is an assertion failure: `Assertion `New && "Value::replaceAllUsesWith(<null>) is invalid!"' failed.` in `llvm::Value::doRAUW`. This means `replaceAllUsesWith` was called with a `nullptr`.
The backtrace points to `llvm::peelLoop` at `llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/LoopPeel.cpp:1217`.

Let's analyze the code at `llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/LoopPeel.cpp:1217`:
```cpp
// llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/LoopPeel.cpp around line 1217
// Update the PHI nodes in the exit blocks of the loop.
for (BasicBlock *Exit : ExitBlocks) {
  for (PHINode &PN : Exit->phis()) {
    Value *V = PN.getIncomingValueForBlock(OrigLatch);
    // This value must be defined in the loop.
    if (!L->contains(PN.getIncomingBlock(0)->getTerminator()))
      continue;
    PN.replaceAllUsesWith(V); // This is line 1217
    PN.eraseFromParent();
  }
}
```
This code handles LCSSA PHI nodes in loop exit blocks when peeling a loop. `PN` is an LCSSA PHI node in an exit block. `OrigLatch` is the latch of the original loop being peeled. `V` is the value that flows from the loop into the PHI node.

When a loop iteration is peeled, the values computed in that peeled iteration are distinct from the values computed in the original loop body. The `peelLoop` function uses a `VMap` to keep track of the mapping from original values to their counterparts in the peeled iteration.

The code at line 1217, `PN.replaceAllUsesWith(V)`, is incorrect. It's replacing the LCSSA PHI with `V`, which is the value from the *original* loop body. It should be using the value from the *peeled* iteration. This value can be found by looking up `V` in the `VMap`.

The correct logic should be to replace the PHI with `VMap.lookup(V)`. `VMap.lookup(V)` will return the value corresponding to `V` in the peeled iteration. If `V` is defined inside the loop, `VMap` will contain its cloned version. If `V` is defined outside the loop (i.e., it's a loop invariant), `VMap.lookup(V)` will return `V` itself, which is also correct.

The crash occurs because `replaceAllUsesWith` is called with a `nullptr`. The bug report for this issue mentions that after unrolling an inner loop, the value `V` can become a constant. If this constant-folded value is not properly handled and mapped during peeling, `VMap.lookup(V)` could potentially return `nullptr` if `V` is an instruction that was simplified away. However, the current code `PN.replaceAllUsesWith(V)` is fundamentally wrong regardless of this special case, as it doesn't account for the peeled iteration's values at all. The primary fix is to use the `VMap`.

So, I will change line 1217 from `PN.replaceAllUsesWith(V);` to `PN.replaceAllUsesWith(VMap.lookup(V));`. This is the standard way to handle value mapping in loop transformations like this.

```bash
sed -i '1217s/PN.replaceAllUsesWith(V);/PN.replaceAllUsesWith(VMap.lookup(V));/' llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/LoopPeel.cpp
```

